library(labelled)
homicide_df = read.csv("homicide-data.csv")
homicide_df = homicide_df %>%
  mutate(
    city_state=str_c(city,state, sep="_"),
    resolved=case_when(
      disposition=="Closed without arrest"~"unsolved",
      disposition=="Open/No arrest"~"unsolved",
      disposition=="Closed by arrest"~"solved",
    )
  )
aggregate_df = 
  homicide_df %>%
  group_by(city_state) %>%
  summarise(
    hom_total = n(),
    hom_unsolved = sum(resolved == "unsolved")
  )

3 Problem 3

  • Make a t-test function
sample_ttest=function(n=30,mu=0, sigma=5) {
  
  samp_data=tibble(
    x=rnorm(n=n, mean=mu, sd=sigma)
  )
  
  samp_data %>%
    summarize(
      mu_hat=mean(x),
      sigma=sd(x))
  
  samp_data %>%
    t.test() %>%
    broom::tidy()
}
  • Create the lists of mu {1,2,3,4,5,6} and rerun
  • Lets simulate a lot
mu =
list(
"mu_1" = 1,
"mu_2" = 2,
"mu_3" = 3,
"mu_4" = 4,
"mu_5" = 5,
"mu_6" = 6
)

output = vector("list", length = 6)

for (i in 1:6) {
output[[i]] = rerun(5, sample_ttest(mu = mu[[i]])) %>% 
  bind_rows() %>% 
  select(estimate, p.value) %>%
  mutate(mu=mu[[i]])
} 

output = bind_rows(output) %>%
  mutate(
  test_results = case_when(
  p.value < .05 ~ "reject",
  p.value >= .05 ~ "fail to reject"
  ))
  • Make a plot showing the proportion of times the null was rejected (the power of the test) on the y axis and the true value of on the x axis. Describe the association between effect size and power.
  • Effect size and power is in positive assoociation. Here, since were doing hypothesis test with mu=0. As, the true value of mu become far from mu=0, it means a higher effect size. From the plot below, we see as the effect size getting larger, power increases.
output %>%
  group_by(mu)%>%
  filter(test_results=="reject") %>%
  count(test_results) %>%
  mutate(power=n/5)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=mu, y=power)) + geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Association between effect size and power") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1,2,3,4,5,6)) +
  theme_light()

  • Make a plot showing the average estimate of on the y axis and the true value of on the x axis. Make a second plot (or overlay on the first) the average estimate of only in samples for which the null was rejected on the y axis and the true value of on the x axis. Is the sample average of across tests for which the null is rejected approximately equal to the true value of ? Why or why not?
  • Yes, the average of mu_hat across tests where the null hypothesis was rejected is approximately equal to the true value of mu. The green line in the second plot is y=x line as a reference. When we comparing the average mu_hat vs.mu, there are comparable.
output %>%
  group_by(mu)%>%
  summarise(average_mu_hat = mean(estimate) ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=mu, y=average_mu_hat)) + geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Average u_hat vs. mu") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1,2,3,4,5,6)) +
  theme_light()

output %>%
  group_by(mu)%>%
  filter(test_results=="reject") %>%
  summarise(average_mu_hat = mean(estimate) ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=mu, y=average_mu_hat)) + geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Average mu_hat vs. mu when reject the null hypothesis") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0,1,2,3,4,5,6), limits = c(0,6)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(0,1,2,3,4,5,6), limits = c(0,6))+
  theme_light() +geom_abline(intercept=0,slope=1, color="green")
